# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: car-t-therapy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] In the 1960s, lymphocytes were discovered to be the mediators of allograft rejection in animals.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Attempts to use T cells to treat transplanted murine tumors required cultivating and manipulating T cells in culture.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Syngeneic lymphocytes were transferred from rodents heavily immunized against the tumor to inhibit growth of small established tumors, becoming the first example of ACT.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Description of T cell growth factor interleukin-2 (IL-2) in 1976 allowed T lymphocytes to be grown *in vitro*, often without loss of effector functions.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] High doses of IL-2 could inhibit tumor growth in mice.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] 1982, studies demonstrated that intravenous immune lymphocytes could treat bulky subcutaneous FBL3 lymphomas.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Administration of IL-2 after cell transfer enhanced therapeutic potential.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] In 1985 IL-2 administration produced durable tumor regressions in some patients with metastatic melanoma.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Lymphocytes infiltrating the stroma of growing, transplantable tumors provided a concentrated source of tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes (TIL) and could stimulate regression of established lung and liver tumors.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] In 1986, human TILs from resected melanomas were found to contain cells that could recognize autologous tumors.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] In 1988 autologous TILs were shown to reduce metastatic melanoma tumors.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Tumor-derived TILs are generally mixtures of CD8+ and CD4+ T cells with few major contaminating cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] In 1989 Zelig Eshhar published the first study in which a T cell's targeting receptor was replaced, and noted that this could be used to direct T cells to attack any kind of cell; this is the essential biotechnology underlying CAR-T therapy.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Responses were often of short duration and faded days after administration.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] In 2002, lymphodepletion using a nonmyeloablative chemotherapy regimen administered immediately before TIL transfer increased cancer regression, as well as the persistent oligoclonal repopulation of the host with the transferred lymphocytes.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] In some patients, the administered antitumor cells represented up to 80% of the CD8+ T cells months after the infusion.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Initially, melanoma was the only cancer that reproducibly yielded useful TIL cultures.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] In 2006 administration of normal circulating lymphocytes transduced with a retrovirus encoding a T-cell receptor (TCR) that recognized the MART-1 melanoma-melanocyte antigen, mediated tumor regression.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] In 2010 administration of lymphocytes genetically engineered to express a chimeric antibody receptor (CAR) against B cell antigen CD19 was shown to mediate regression of an advanced B cell lymphoma.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] By 2010, doctors had begun experimental treatments for leukemia patients using CD19-targeted T cells with added DNA to stimulate cell division.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] As of 2015 trials had treated about 350 leukemia and lymphoma patients.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Antigen CD19 appears only on B cells, which go awry in lymphoma and leukemia.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Loss of B cells can be countered with immunoglobulin.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Startups including Juno Therapeutics exploit the combination of aggressive tumors and FDA willingness to approve potential therapies for such ailments to accelerate approvals for new therapies.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] In checkpoint therapy, antibodies bind to molecules involved in T-cell regulation to remove inhibitory pathways that block T-cell responses, known as immune checkpoint therapy.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] As of 2015 the technique had expanded to treat cervical cancer, lymphoma, leukemia, bile duct cancer and neuroblastoma and in 2016, lung cancer, breast cancer, sarcoma and melanoma.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] In 2016, CD19-specific chimeric antigen receptor (CAR)-modified T cells were used to treat patients with relapsed and refractory CD19+ B cell malignancies, including B cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia (B-ALL) harboring rearrangement of the mixed lineage leukemia (MLL) gene with CD19 CAR-T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] In 2016, researchers developed a technique that used cancer cells' RNA to produce T cells and an immune response.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] They encased the RNA in a negatively charged fatty membrane.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] *In vivo*, this electrical charge guided the particles towards the patient's dendritic immune cells that specify immune system targets.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] In 2017, researchers announced the first use of donor cells (rather than the patients' own cells) to defeat leukemia in two infants for whom other treatments had failed.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] The cells had four genetic modifications.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] One changed the cells so that they did not attack all the cells of another person.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Another modification made tumor cells their target.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] As of February 2024, 27 advanced cell therapy products (CTPs) were approved by FDA.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] In melanoma, a resected melanoma specimen is digested into a single-cell suspension or divided into multiple tumor fragments.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] The result is individually grown in IL-2.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] They destroy the tumors in the sample within 2 to 3 weeks.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] They then produce pure cultures of lymphocytes that can be tested for reactivity against other tumors, in coculture assays.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Individual cultures are then expanded in the presence of IL-2 and excess irradiated anti-CD3 antibodies.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] The latter targets the epsilon subunit within the human CD3 complex of the TCR.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] 5–6 weeks after resecting the tumor, up to 1011 lymphocytes can be obtained.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Prior to infusion, a lymphodepleting preparative regimen is undergone, typically 60 mg/kg cyclophosphamide for 2 days and 25 mg/m2 fludarabine administered for 5 days.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] This substantially increases infused cell persistence and the incidence and duration of clinical responses.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Then cells and IL-2 at 720,000 IU/kg to tolerance are infused.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Interleukin-21 may play an important role in enhancing the efficacy of T cell based *in vitro* therapies.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] In early trials, preparing engineered T cells cost $75,000 to manufacture cells for each patient.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Interleukin-2 is normally added to the extracted T cells to boost their effectiveness, but in high doses it can have a toxic effect.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] The reduced number of injected T cells is accompanied by reduced IL-2, thereby reducing side effects.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] *In vitro* tests on melanoma and kidney cancer models met expectations.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] In 2016 *Strep*-tag II sequences were introduced into synthetic CAR or natural T-cell receptors to serve as a marker for identification, rapid purification, tailoring spacer length for optimal function and selective, antibody-coated, microbead-driven, large-scale expansion.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] This facilitates cGMP manufacturing of pure populations of engineered T cells and enables *in vivo* tracking and retrieval of transferred cells for downstream research applications.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Antitumor receptors genetically engineered into normal T cells can be used for therapy.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] T cells can be redirected by the integration of genes encoding either conventional alpha-beta TCRs or CARs.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] CARs (Chimeric Antibody Receptors) were pioneered in the late 1980s and can be constructed by linking the variable regions of the antibody heavy and light chains to intracellular signaling chains such as CD3-zeta, potentially including costimulatory domains encoding CD28 or CD137.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] CARs can provide recognition of cell surface components not restricted to major histocompatibility complexes (MHC).
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] They can be introduced into T cells with high efficiency using viral vectors.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Improved antitumor responses have been seen in mouse and monkey models using T cells in early differentiation stages (such as naïve or central memory cells).
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] CD8+ T cells follow a progressive pathway of differentiation from naïve T cells into stem cell memory, central memory, effector memory, and ultimately terminally differentiated effector T cell populations.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] CD8+ T cells paradoxically lose antitumor power as they acquire the ability to lyse target cells and to produce the cytokine interferon-γ, qualities otherwise thought to be important for antitumor efficacy.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Differentiation state is inversely related to proliferation and persistence.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Age is negatively correlated with clinical effectiveness.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] CD8+ T cells can exist in a stem cell–like state, capable of clonal proliferation.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Human T memory stem cells express a gene program that enables them to proliferate extensively and differentiate into other T cell populations.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] CD4+ T cells can also promote tumor rejection.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] CD4+ T cells enhance CD8+ T cell function and can directly destroy tumor cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Evidence suggests that T helper 17 cells can promote sustained antitumor immunity.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Other modes of enhancing immuno-therapy include targeting so-called intrinsic immune checkpoint blockades.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Many of these intrinsic regulators include molecules with ubiquitin ligase activity, including CBLB.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] More recently, CISH, a molecule with ubiquitin ligase activity, was found to be induced by T cell receptor ligation (TCR) and suppressed by targeting the critical signaling intermediate PLC-gamma-1.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] The deletion of CISH in effector T cells dramatically augments TCR signaling and subsequent effector cytokine release, proliferation and survival.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] The adoptive transfer of tumor-specific effector T cells knocked out or knocked down CISH, resulting in a significant increase in functional avidity and sustained tumor immunity.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Surprisingly no changes in activity of STAT5, CISH's purported target.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Thus CISH represents a new class of T-cell intrinsic immunologic checkpoints with the potential to enhance adoptive immunotherapies.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Neither tumor bulk nor metastasis site affect the likelihood of achieving a complete cancer regression.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Of 34 complete responders in two trials, one recurred.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Only one patient with complete regression received more than one treatment.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Prior treatment with targeted therapy using Braf inhibitor vemurafenib (Zelboraf) did not affect the likelihood that melanoma patients would experience an objective response.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Prior failed immunotherapies did not reduce the odds of objective response.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] An emerging treatment modality for various diseases is the transfer of stem cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Clinically, this approach has been exploited to transfer either immune-promoting or tolerogenic cells (often lymphocytes) to either enhance immunity against viruses and cancer or to promote tolerance in the setting of autoimmune disease, such as Type I diabetes or rheumatoid arthritis.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Cells used in adoptive therapy may be genetically modified using recombinant DNA technology.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] One example of this in the case of T cell adoptive therapy is the addition of CARs to redirect the specificity of cytotoxic and helper T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] The transfer of regulatory T cells has been used to treat Type 1 diabetes and others.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Trials began in the 1990s and accelerated beginning in 2010.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Targeting normal, nonmutated antigenic targets that are expressed on normal tissues, but overexpressed on tumors has led to severe on-target, off-tumor toxicity.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Toxicities can also result when previously unknown cross-reactivities are seen that target normal self-proteins expressed in vital organs.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Cancer-testes antigen MAGE-A3 is not known to be expressed in any normal tissues.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] However, targeting an HLA-A*0201–restricted peptide in MAGE-A3 caused severe damage to gray matter in the brain, because this TCR also recognized a different but related epitope that is expressed at low levels in the brain.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] That CARs are potentially toxic to self-antigens was observed after infusion of CAR T cells specific for ERBB2.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Two patients died when treated with an HLA-A1–restricted MAGE-A3–specific TCR whose affinity was enhanced by a site-specific mutagenesis.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Cancer-testis antigens are a family of intracellular proteins that are expressed during fetal development, but with little expression in normal adult tissues.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] More than 100 such molecules are epigenetically up-regulated in from 10 to 80% of cancer types.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] However, they lack high levels of protein expression.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Approximately 10% of common cancers appear to express enough protein to be of interest for antitumor T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Low levels of some cancer-testes antigens are expressed in normal tissues, with associated toxicities.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] The NYESO-1 cancer-testes antigen has been targeted via a human TCR transduced into autologous cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] ORs were seen in 5 of 11 patients with metastatic melanoma and 4 of 6 patients with highly refractory synovial cell sarcoma.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] "Suicide switches" let doctors kill engineered T cells in emergencies which threaten patient survival.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Cytokine release syndrome is another side effect and can be a function of therapeutic effectiveness.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] As the tumor is destroyed, it releases large quantities of cell signaling protein molecules.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] This effect killed at least seven patients.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Molecules shared among tumors and nonessential normal organs represent potential ACT targets, despite the related toxicity.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] For example, the CD19 molecule is expressed on more than 90% of B cell malignancies and on non-plasma B cells at all differentiation stages and has been successfully used to treat patients with follicular lymphoma, large-cell lymphomas, chronic lymphocytic leukemia and acute lymphoblastic leukemia.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Toxicity against CD19 results in B cell loss in circulation and in bone marrow that can be overcome by periodic immunoglobulin infusions.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] Multiple other B cell antigens are being studied as targets, including CD22, CD23, ROR-1 and the immunoglobulin light-chain idiotype expressed by the individual cancer.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] CARs targeting either CD33 or CD123 have been studied as a therapy for patients with acute myeloid leukemia, though the expression of these molecules on normal precursors can lead to prolonged myeloablation.
[src:car-t-therapy/adoptive-cell-transfer] BCMA is a tumor necrosis factor receptor family protein expressed on mature B cells and plasma cells and can be targeted on multiple myeloma.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] In biology, **chimeric antigen receptors** (**CARs**)—also known as **chimeric immunoreceptors**, **chimeric T cell receptors** or **artificial T cell receptors**—are receptor proteins that have been engineered to give T cells the new ability to target a specific antigen.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The receptors are chimeric in that they combine both antigen-binding and T cell activating functions into a single receptor.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] CAR T cell therapy uses T cells engineered with CARs to treat cancer.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] T cells are modified to recognize cancer cells and destroy them.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The standard approach is to harvest T cells from patients, genetically alter them, then infuse the resulting CAR T cells into patients to attack their tumors.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] CAR T cells can be derived either autologously from T cells in a patient's own blood or allogeneically from those of a donor.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Once isolated, these T cells are genetically engineered to express a specific CAR, using a vector derived from an engineered lentivirus such as HIV (see lentiviral vector in gene therapy).
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The CAR programs the T cells to target an antigen present on the tumor cell surface.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] For safety, CAR T cells are engineered to be specific to an antigen that is expressed on a tumor cell but not on healthy cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] After the modified T cells are infused into a patient, they act as a "living drug" against cancer cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] When they come in contact with their targeted antigen on a cell's surface, T cells bind to it and become activated, then proceed to proliferate and become cytotoxic.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The surface of CAR T cells can bear either of two types of co-receptors, CD4 and CD8.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] These two cell types, called CD4+ and CD8+, respectively, have different and interacting cytotoxic effects.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Therapies employing a 1-to-1 ratio of the cell types apparently provide synergistic antitumor effects.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The first chimeric receptors containing portions of an antibody and the T cell receptor were described in 1987 by Yoshihisa Kuwana et al., at Fujita Health University and Kyowa Hakko Kogyo, Co.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Ltd., in Japan, and independently in 1989 by Gideon Gross and Zelig Eshhar at the Weizmann Institute in Israel.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Originally termed "T-bodies", these early approaches combined an antibody's ability to specifically bind to diverse targets with the constant domains of the TCR-α or TCR-β proteins.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] In 1991, chimeric receptors containing the intracellular signaling domain of CD3ζ were shown to activate T cell signaling by Arthur Weiss at the University of California, San Francisco.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] This work prompted CD3ζ intracellular domains to be added to chimeric receptors with antibody-like extracellular domains, commonly single-chain fraction variable (scFv) domains, as well as proteins such as CD4, subsequently termed first generation CARs.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Similar early clinical trials of CAR T cells in solid tumors in the 1990s using first generation CARs targeting a solid tumor antigens such as MUC1 did not show long-term persistence of the transferred T cells or result in significant remissions.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] In the early 2000s, co-stimulatory domains such as CD28 or 4-1BB were added to first generation CAR's CD3ζ intracellular domain.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Termed second generation CARs, these constructs showed greater persistence and improved tumor clearance in pre-clinical models.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] As of 2022, six CAR T therapies were FDA-approved.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The first step in the production of CAR T-cells is the isolation of T cells from human blood.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] CAR T-cells may be manufactured either from the patient's own blood, known as an autologous treatment, or from the blood of a healthy donor, known as an allogeneic treatment.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The manufacturing process is the same in both cases; only the choice of initial blood donor is different.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] First, leukocytes are isolated using a blood cell separator in a process known as leukocyte apheresis.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Peripheral blood mononuclear cells (PBMCs) are then separated and collected.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The products of leukocyte apheresis are then transferred to a cell-processing center.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] In the cell processing center, specific T cells are stimulated so that they will actively proliferate and expand to large numbers.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] To drive their expansion, T cells are typically treated with the cytokine interleukin 2 (IL-2) and anti-CD3 antibodies.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Anti-CD3/CD28 antibodies are also used in some protocols.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The expanded T cells are purified and then transduced with a gene encoding the engineered CAR via a retroviral vector, typically either an integrating gammaretrovirus (RV) or a lentiviral (LV) vector.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] These vectors are very safe in modern times due to a partial deletion of the U3 region.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The new gene editing tool CRISPR/Cas9 has recently been used instead of retroviral vectors to integrate the CAR gene into specific sites in the genome.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The efficiency of CAR T-cell production depends on whether open or automated closed systems are used and on the processing type, such as low-shear processing or intensive magnetic separation.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The patient undergoes lymphodepletion chemotherapy prior to the introduction of the engineered CbAR T-cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The depletion of the number of circulating leukocytes in the patient upregulates the number of cytokines that are produced and reduces competition for resources, which helps to promote the expansion of the engineered CAR T-cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] As of March 2019, there were around 364 ongoing clinical trials happening globally involving CAR T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The majority of those trials target blood cancers: CAR T therapies account for more than half of all trials for hematological malignancies.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] CD19 continues to be the most popular antigen target, followed by BCMA (commonly expressed in multiple myeloma).
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] In 2016, studies began to explore the viability of other antigens, such as CD20.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Trials for solid tumors are less dominated by CAR T, with about half of cell therapy-based trials involving other platforms such as NK cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] T cells are genetically engineered to express chimeric antigen receptors specifically directed toward antigens on a patient's tumor cells, then infused into the patient where they attack and kill the cancer cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Adoptive transfer of T cells expressing CARs is a promising anti-cancer therapeutic, because CAR-modified T cells can be engineered to target potentially any tumor associated antigen.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Early CAR T cell research has focused on blood cancers.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The first approved treatments use CARs that target the antigen CD19, present in B-cell-derived cancers such as acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL) and diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL).
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] There are also efforts underway to engineer CARs targeting many other blood cancer antigens, including CD30 in refractory Hodgkin lymphoma; CD33, CD123, and FLT3 in acute myeloid leukemia (AML); and BCMA in multiple myeloma.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Aside from CD19, CARs targeting the multiple myeloma antigen B-cell maturation antigen (BCMA) have achieved the most clinical success so far.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] CARs targeting BCMA were initially reported by Robert Carpenter and James Kochenderfer et al.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Anti-BCMA CAR T cells have now been tested in many clinical trials, and anti-BCMA CAR T-cell products have been approved by the U.S.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] CAR T (CARv3-TEAM-E) cells have been reported to be effective in treating glioblastoma.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] In a small trial, a single infusion demonstrated rapid tumor regression in a matter of days.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Solid tumors have presented a more difficult target.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Identification of good antigens has been challenging: such antigens must be highly expressed on the majority of cancer cells, but largely absent on normal tissues.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] CAR T cells are also not trafficked efficiently into the center of solid tumor masses, and the hostile tumor microenvironment suppresses T cell activity.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] CAR T can be used to target autoimmune diseases by eradicating auto-reactive populations of memory B cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] A classical example is the targeting of CD19 to eradicate the entire B cell population in lupus erythematosus.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] It has been investigated as a treatment for ulcerative colitis and rheumatoid arthritis.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Clinical trials have launched for systemic sclerosis, myositis and rheumatoid arthritis.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Researchers are trying other target molecules so as to not kill as many innocent bystanders.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] A gentler way involves modifying another kind of T cell, the regulatory T cells (Treg), responsible for tolerance to antigens.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] A CAR Treg could confer tolerance to a specific antigen, which could be utilized in organ transplantation or rheumatologic diseases like lupus.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] There are serious side effects that result from CAR T-cells being introduced into the body, including cytokine release syndrome and neurotoxicity.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Because it is a relatively new treatment, there are few data about the long-term effects of CAR T-cell therapy.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] There are still concerns about long-term patient survival, as well as pregnancy complications in female patients treated with CAR T-cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Anaphylaxis may be a side effect, as the CAR is made with a foreign monoclonal antibody, and as a result provokes an immune response.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] On-target/off-tumor recognition occurs when the CAR T-cell recognizes the correct antigen, but the antigen is expressed on healthy, non-pathogenic tissue.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] This results in the CAR T-cells attacking non-tumor tissue, such as healthy B cells that express CD19 causing B-cell aplasia.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The severity of this adverse effect can vary but the combination of prior immunosuppression, lymphodepleting chemotherapy and on-target effects causing hypogammaglobulinaemia and prolonged cytopenias places patients at increased risk of serious infections.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Marco Ruella and others have shown that less intensive lymphodepletion strategies such us bendamustine might reduce CART-related toxicities such as neurotoxicity, cytopenias, and neutropenic fever.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Comprehensive dental evaluation and treatment before CAR T-cell therapy is recommended for reducing the risk of oral and systemic infections during the neutropenic phase.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] There is also the unlikely possibility that the engineered CAR T-cells will themselves become transformed into cancerous cells through insertional mutagenesis, due to the viral vector inserting the CAR gene into a tumor suppressor or oncogene in the host T cell's genome.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Some retroviral (RV) vectors carry a lower risk than lentiviral (LV) vectors.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] However, both have the potential to be oncogenic.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Genomic sequencing analysis of CAR insertion sites in T cells has been established for better understanding of CAR T-cell function and persistence *in vivo*.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The most common issue after treatment with CAR T-cells is cytokine release syndrome (CRS), a condition in which the immune system is activated and releases an increased number of inflammatory cytokines.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The clinical manifestation of this syndrome resembles sepsis with high fever, fatigue, myalgia, nausea, capillary leakages, tachycardia and other cardiac dysfunction, liver failure, and kidney impairment.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] CRS occurs in almost all patients treated with CAR T-cell therapy; in fact, the presence of CRS is a diagnostic marker that indicates the CAR T-cells are working as intended to kill the cancer cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The severity of CRS does not correlate with an increased response to the treatment, but rather higher disease burden.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Severe cytokine release syndrome can be managed with immunosuppressants such as corticosteroids, and with tocilizumab, an anti-IL-6 monoclonal antibody.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Early intervention using tocilizumab was shown to reduce the frequency of severe CRS in multiple studies without affecting the therapeutic effect of the treatment.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] A novel strategy aimed to ameliorate CRS is based on the simultaneous expression of an artificial non-signaling IL-6 receptor on the surface of CAR T-cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] This construct neutralizes macrophage-derived IL-6 through sequestration, thus decreasing the severity of CRS without interfering with the antitumor capability of the CAR T-cell itself.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Neurological toxicity is also often associated with CAR T-cell treatment.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The underlying mechanism is poorly understood, and may or may not be related to CRS.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Clinical manifestations include delirium, the partial loss of the ability to speak coherently while still having the ability to interpret language (expressive aphasia), lowered alertness (obtundation), and seizures.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] During some clinical trials, deaths caused by neurotoxicity have occurred.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The main cause of death from neurotoxicity is cerebral edema.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] In a study carried out by Juno Therapeutics, Inc., five patients enrolled in the trial died as a result of cerebral edema.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Two of the patients were treated with cyclophosphamide alone and the remaining three were treated with a combination of cyclophosphamide and fludarabine.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] In another clinical trial sponsored by the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center, there was one reported case of irreversible and fatal neurological toxicity 122 days after the administration of CAR T-cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Hypokinetic movement disorder (parkinsonism, or movement and neurocognitive treatment emergent adverse events) has been observed with BCMA-chimeric antigen receptor (CAR) T-cell treatment for multiple myeloma.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Tumor cells have the ability to evolve new mechanisms for evasion of the immune system after its initial response.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Some of these methods include downregulating the expression of their Major Histocompatibility Complex, secreting immunosuppressive factors, or altering their antigen expression, limiting the ability of conventional T cells to recognize and kill them.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] CAR (Chimeric Antigen Receptor) T cells overcome this limitation by recognizing tumor antigens directly through their engineered receptor, therefore bypassing the need for MHC presentation.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] In addition, CAR T Cell Therapy offers the included advantages of: Higher response rates in refractory cancers, longer term remission because they remain in the body for years, and they are a more personalized treatment approach because they use the body's own T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Chimeric antigen receptors combine many facets of normal T cell activation into a single protein.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] They link an extracellular antigen recognition domain to an intracellular signalling domain, which activates the T cell when an antigen is bound.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] CARs are composed of four regions: an antigen recognition domain, an extracellular hinge region, a transmembrane domain, and an intracellular T cell signaling domain.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The antigen recognition domain is exposed to the outside of the cell, in the ectodomain portion of the receptor.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] It interacts with potential target molecules and is responsible for targeting the CAR T cell to any cell expressing a matching molecule.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The antigen recognition domain is typically derived from the variable regions of a monoclonal antibody linked together as a single-chain variable fragment (scFv).
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] An scFv is a chimeric protein made up of the light (VL) and heavy (VH) chains of immunoglobins, connected with a short linker peptide.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] These VL and VH regions are selected in advance for their binding ability to the target antigen (such as CD19).
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The linker between the two chains consists of hydrophilic residues with stretches of glycine and serine in it for flexibility as well as stretches of glutamate and lysine for added solubility.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] VH, VHH, VNAR) have been engineered and developed as antigen recognition domains in the CAR format due to their high transduction efficiency in T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] In addition to antibody fragments, non-antibody-based approaches have also been used to direct CAR specificity, usually taking advantage of ligand/receptor pairs that normally bind to each other.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Cytokines, innate immune receptors, TNF receptors, growth factors, and structural proteins have all been successfully used as CAR antigen recognition domains.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The hinge, also called a spacer, is a small structural domain that sits between the antigen recognition region and the cell's outer membrane.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] An ideal hinge enhances the flexibility of the scFv receptor head, reducing the spatial constraints between the CAR and its target antigen.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] This promotes antigen binding and synapse formation between the CAR T cells and target cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Hinge sequences are often based on membrane-proximal regions from other immune molecules including IgG, CD8, and CD28.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The transmembrane domain is a structural component, consisting of a hydrophobic alpha helix that spans the cell membrane.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] It anchors the CAR to the plasma membrane, bridging the extracellular hinge and antigen recognition domains with the intracellular signaling region.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] This domain is essential for the stability of the receptor as a whole.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Generally, the transmembrane domain from the most membrane-proximal component of the endodomain is used, but different transmembrane domains result in different receptor stability.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The CD28 transmembrane domain is known to result in a highly expressed, stable receptor.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Using the CD3-zeta transmembrane domain is not recommended, as it can result in incorporation of the artificial TCR into the native TCR.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The intracellular T cell signaling domain lies in the receptor's endodomain, inside the cell.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] After an antigen is bound to the external antigen recognition domain, CAR receptors cluster together and transmit an activation signal.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Then the internal cytoplasmic end of the receptor perpetuates signaling inside the T cell.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Normal T cell activation relies on the phosphorylation of immunoreceptor tyrosine-based activation motifs (ITAMs) present in the cytoplasmic domain of CD3ζ.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] To mimic this process, CD3ζ's cytoplasmic domain is commonly used as the main CAR endodomain component.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Other ITAM-containing domains have also been tried, but are not as effective.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] T cells also require co-stimulatory molecules in addition to CD3ζ signaling in order to persist after activation.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] For this reason, the endodomains of CAR receptors typically also include one or more chimeric domains from co-stimulatory proteins.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Signaling domains from a wide variety of co-stimulatory molecules have been successfully tested, including CD28, CD27, CD134 (OX40), and CD137 (4-1BB).
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Although the initial clinical remission rates after CAR T cell therapy in all patients are as high as 90%, long-term survival rates are much lower.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The cause is typically the emergence of leukemia cells that do not express CD19 and so evade recognition by the CD19–CAR T cells, a phenomenon known as antigen escape.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Preclinical studies developing CAR T cells with dual targeting of CD19 plus CD22 or CD19 plus CD20 have demonstrated promise, and trials studying bispecific targeting to circumvent CD19 down-regulation are ongoing.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] In 2018, a version of CAR was developed that is referred to as SUPRA CAR, or split, universal, and programmable.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Multiple mechanisms can be deployed to finely regulate the activity of SUPRA CAR, which limits overactivation.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] In contrast to the traditional CAR design, SUPRA CAR allows targeting of multiple antigens without further genetic modification of immune cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] In 2026, CART4-34 therapy targeted B cell receptors carrying the gene *IGHV4-34* — thought to be involved in immune response and which appears at high levels in tumor cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] In mice models CART4-34 therapy was as effective as CD19 CAR-T therapy at destroying tumor cells in diffuse large B-cell lymphoma.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] *IGHV4-34* gene is rare in healthy cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The therapy does not target CD19, reducing/eliminating immune system effects.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Treatment of antigenically heterogeneous tumors can be achieved by administration of a mixture of the desired antigen-specific adaptors.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Fourth generation CARs (also known as TRUCKs or armored CARs) further add factors that enhance T cell expansion, persistence, and anti-tumoral activity.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] This can include cytokines, such is IL-2, IL-5, IL-12 and co-stimulatory ligands.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Adding a synthetic control mechanism to engineered T cells allows doctors to precisely control the persistence or activity of the T cells in the patient's body, with the goal of reducing toxic side effects.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The major control techniques trigger T cell death or limit T cell activation, and often regulate the T cells via a separate drug that can be introduced or withheld as needed.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] when activated by an extracellular molecule.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] (iCasp9) are two types of suicide genes that have been integrated into CAR T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] with high specificity to the small molecule rimiducid/AP1903, and a gene encoding a pro-domain-deleted human caspase 9.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Dosing the patient with rimiducid activates the suicide system, leading to rapid apoptosis of the genetically modified T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Although both the HSV-TK and iCasp9 systems demonstrate a noticeable function as a safety switch in clinical trials, some defects limit their application.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] HSV-TK is virus-derived and may be immunogenic to humans.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] It is also currently unclear whether the suicide gene strategies will act quickly enough in all situations to halt dangerous off-tumor cytotoxicity.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] CAR T cells are engineered to express two tumor-associated antigen receptors at the same time, reducing the likelihood that the T cells will attack non-tumor cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Dual-antigen receptor CAR T cells have been reported to have less intense side effects.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] study in mice shows that dual-receptor CAR T cells effectively eradicated prostate cancer and achieved complete long-term survival.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] In this system, CAR T cells can only function in the presence of both tumor antigen and a benign exogenous molecule.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] To achieve this, the CAR T cell's engineered chimeric antigen receptor is split into two separate proteins that must come together in order to function.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The first receptor protein typically contains the extracellular antigen binding domain, while the second protein contains the downstream signaling elements and co-stimulatory molecules (such as CD3ζ and 4-1BB).
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] In the presence of an exogenous molecule (such as a rapamycin analog), the binding and signaling proteins dimerize together, allowing the CAR T cells to attack the tumor.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Bispecific molecules target both a tumor-associated antigen and the CD3 molecule on the surface of T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] This ensures that the T cells cannot become activated unless they are in close physical proximity to a tumor cell.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The anti-CD20/CD3 bispecific molecule shows high specificity to both malignant B cells and cancer cells in mice.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] is another bifunctional molecule used in this strategy.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] FITC can redirect and regulate the activity of the FITC-specific CAR T cells toward tumor cells with folate receptors.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Due to high costs, researchers are seeking less expensive ways to modify cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] *In situ* manufacturing eliminates expensive steps.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Delivery systems include immune-evasive lentiviral vectors and targeted lipid nanoparticles.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Another approach exploits bioinstructive materials.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Shortening or eliminating the activation and expansion steps is another cost reduction strategy.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Recent advancements in CAR T-cell therapy have focused on alternative activating domains to enhance efficacy and overcome resistance in solid tumors.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] For instance, Toll-like receptor 4 (TLR4) signaling components can be incorporated into CAR constructs to modulate cytokine production and boost T-cell activation and proliferation, leading to enhanced CAR T-cell expansion and persistence.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Similarly, the FYN kinase, a member of the Src family kinases involved in T-cell receptor signaling, can be integrated to improve the signaling cascade within CAR T-cells, resulting in better targeting and elimination of cancer cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Additionally, KIR-based CARs (KIR-CAR), which use the transmembrane and intracellular domains of the activating receptor KIR2DS2 combined with the DAP-12 signaling adaptor, have shown improved T-cell proliferation and antitumor activity.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] These strategies, including the use of nonconventional costimulatory molecules like MyD88/CD40, highlight the innovative approaches being taken to optimize CAR T-cell therapies for more effective cancer treatments.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The cost of CAR T cell therapies has been criticized, with the initial costs of tisagenlecleucel and axicabtagene ciloleucel at $375,000 and $475,000, respectively.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] The high cost of CAR T therapies is due to complex cellular manufacturing in specialized good manufacturing practice (GMP) facilities as well as the high level of hospital care necessary after CAR T cells are administered due to risks such as cytokine release syndrome.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] In the United States, CAR T cell therapies are covered by Medicare and by many but not all private insurers.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Manufacturers of CAR T cells have developed alternative payment programs due to the high cost of CAR T therapy, such as by requiring payment only if the CAR T therapy induces a complete remission by a certain time point after treatment.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Additionally, CAR T cell therapies are not available worldwide yet.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] CAR T cell therapies have been approved in China, Australia, Singapore, the United Kingdom, and some European countries.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] In February 2022 Brazil approved tisagenlecleucel (Kymriah) treatment.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] As a promising strategy to reduce complexity and cost of CAR T-cell therapy, *in vivo* CAR T-cell therapy has recently emerged.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] This approach entails the direct delivery of CAR-encoding genetic material into a patient's T-cells in situ, typically via functionalised viral vectors or targeted nanocarriers, eliminating the necessity for ex vivo cell harvesting, separation, modification, expansion and reinfusion.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Potentially related risks involve challenges with precise T cell targeting, off-tumour on-target (OTOT) toxicities or with sustained CAR expression.
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] However, in vivo CAR T therapy might mitigate some of the associated risks of systemic toxicities of classic ex vivo CAR T therapy like cytokine release syndrome (CRS) or Immune effector cell-associated neurotoxicity (ICANS).
[src:car-t-therapy/chimeric-antigen-receptor-t-cell] Besides an estimated reduction in costs by "an order of magnitude" compared to classic ex vivo CAR therapy, the biggest potential advantage of in vivo CAR T-cell transfection is a reduction of timelines, as 20% of patients die before their CAR T-cell therapy has been produced in the USA.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] In immunology, **cytokine release syndrome** (**CRS**) is a form of systemic inflammatory response syndrome (SIRS) that can be triggered by a variety of factors such as infections and certain drugs.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] It refers to cytokine storm syndromes (CSS) and occurs when large numbers of white blood cells are activated and release inflammatory cytokines, which in turn activate yet more white blood cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] CRS is also an adverse effect of some monoclonal antibody medications, as well as adoptive T-cell therapies.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] The term **cytokine storm** is often used interchangeably with CRS but, despite the fact that they have similar clinical phenotype, their characteristics are different.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] When occurring as a result of a therapy, CRS symptoms may be delayed until days or weeks after treatment.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Immediate-onset CRS is a cytokine storm, although severe cases of CRS have also been called cytokine storms.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Symptoms include fever that tends to fluctuate, fatigue, loss of appetite, muscle and joint pain, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, rashes, fast breathing, rapid heartbeat, low blood pressure, seizures, headache, confusion, delirium, hallucinations, tremor, and loss of coordination.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] CRS occurs when large numbers of white blood cells, including B cells, T cells, natural killer cells, macrophages, dendritic cells, and monocytes are activated and release inflammatory cytokines, which activate more white blood cells in a positive feedback loop of pathogenic inflammation.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Immune cells are activated by stressed or infected cells through receptor-ligand interactions.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] This can occur when the immune system is fighting pathogens, as cytokines produced by immune cells recruit more effector immune cells such as T-cells and inflammatory monocytes (which differentiate into macrophages) to the site of inflammation or infection.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] In addition, pro-inflammatory cytokines binding their cognate receptor on immune cells results in activation and stimulation of further cytokine production.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Adoptive cell transfer of autologous T-cells modified with chimeric antigen receptors (CAR-T cell therapy) also causes CRS.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Serum samples of patients with CAR-T associated CRS have elevated levels of IL-6, IFN-γ, IL-8 (CXCL8), IL-10, GM-CSF, MIP-1α/β, MCP-1 (CCL2), CXCL9, and CXCL10 (IP-10).
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] The most predictive biomarkers 36h after CAR-T infusion of CRS are a fever ≥38.9 °C (102 °F) and elevated levels of MCP-1 in serum.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Many of the cytokines elevated in CRS are not produced by CAR-T cells, but by myeloid cells that are pathogenically licensed through T-cell-mediated activating mechanisms.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] For example, in vitro co-culture experiments have demonstrated IL-6, MCP-1, and MIP-1 are not produced by CAR-T cells, but rather by inflammatory myeloid lineage cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] In vivo models have demonstrated NSG (NOD/SCID/γ-chain deficient mice) with defects of both lymphocyte and myeloid lineage compartments do not develop CRS after CAR-T cell infusion.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Although severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) is sufficiently cleared by the early acute phase anti-viral response in most individuals, some progress to a hyperinflammatory condition, often with life-threatening pulmonary involvement.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] This systemic hyperinflammation results in inflammatory lymphocytic and monocytic infiltration of the lung and the heart, causing ARDS and cardiac failure.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Patients with fulminant COVID-19 and ARDS have classical serum biomarkers of CRS including elevated CRP, LDH, IL-6, and ferritin.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis and Epstein-Barr virus-related hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis are caused by extreme elevations in cytokines and can be regarded as one form of severe cytokine release syndrome.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Cytokine reaction syndrome may also be induced by certain medications, such as the CD20 antibody rituximab and the CD19 CAR T cell tisagenlecleucel.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] The experimental drug TGN1412—also known as Theralizumab—caused extremely serious symptoms when given to six participants in a Phase I trial.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] A controlled and limited CRS is triggered by active fever therapy with mixed bacterial vaccines (MBV) according to Coley; it is used for oncological and certain chronic diseases.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] CRS has also arisen with biotherapeutics such as COVID-19 vaccines (Frontiers of Immunology 2022 13: 967226) and monoclonal antibodies intended to suppress or activate the immune system through receptors on white blood cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] CRS needs to be distinguished from symptoms of the disease itself and, in the case of drugs, from other adverse effects; for example, tumor lysis syndrome requires different interventions.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] As of 2015, differential diagnoses depended on the judgement of doctors, as there were no objective tests.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] CRS is a form of systemic inflammatory response syndrome and is an adverse effect of some drugs.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Severe CRS caused by some drugs can be prevented by using lower doses, infusing slowly, and administering anti-histamines or corticosteroids before and during administration of the drug.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] A modified Chandler loop model can be used as a preclinical tool to assess infusion reactions.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Treatment for less severe CRS is supportive, addressing the symptoms like fever, muscle pain, or fatigue.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Moderate CRS requires oxygen therapy and giving fluids and antihypotensive agents to raise blood pressure.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] For moderate to severe CRS, the use of immunosuppressive agents like corticosteroids may be necessary, but judgment must be used to avoid negating the effect of drugs intended to activate the immune system.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Tocilizumab, an anti-IL-6 monoclonal antibody, was FDA approved for steroid-refractory CRS based on retrospective case study data.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Lenzilumab, an anti-GM-CSF monoclonal antibody, is also clinically proven to be effective at managing cytokine release by reducing activation of myeloid cells and decreasing the production of IL-1, IL-6, MCP-1, MIP-1, and IP-10.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Additionally, as a soluble cytokine blockade, it will not increase serum levels of GM-CSF (a phenomenon seen with tocilizumab and IL-6).
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Although frequently used to treat severe CRS in people with ARDS, corticosteroids and NSAIDs have been evaluated in clinical trials and have shown no effect on lung mechanics, gas exchange, or beneficial outcome in early established ARDS.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Minor and moderate CRS are common side effects of immune-modulating antibody therapies and CAR-T therapies.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Key therapeutic targets to abrogate hyper-inflammation in CRS are IL-1, IL-6, and GM-CSF.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] An in vivo model found that GM-CSF knockout CAR-T cells do not induce CRS in mice.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] However, IL-1 knockout and IL-6 knockout hosts (whose myeloid cells are deficient in IL-1 and IL-6, respectively) were susceptible to CRS after the administration of wild-type CAR-T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] It is thought this may be because while blockade of IL-1 and IL-6 are myeloid-derived cytokines are thus too far downstream of the inflammatory cascade.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Moreover, while tocilizumab (anti-IL-6R monoclonal antibody) may have an anti-inflammatory and antipyretic effect, it has been shown to increase serum levels of IL-6 by saturating the receptor, thus driving the cytokine across the blood brain barrier (BBB) and worsening neurotoxicity.
[src:car-t-therapy/cytokine-release-syndrome] Monoclonal antibody blockade of GM-CSF with lenzilumab has been demonstrated to protect mice from CAR-T associated CRS and neurotoxicity while maintaining anti-leukemic efficacy.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] A broader definition of immunotherapy applies beyond oncology, including strategies to stimulate or suppress immune activity against other diseases such as autoimmune disorders, infectious diseases, and allergies.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] These approaches may involve vaccines, immune modulators, or monoclonal antibodies designed to alter immune responses, either to boost protection against pathogens or to reduce damaging inflammation.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Immunotherapy includes both passive methods, like monoclonal antibodies that mark abnormal cells for immune destruction, and active methods, such as cancer vaccines, immune checkpoint inhibitors, adoptive cell transfer, and cytokine therapies.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Advances in immunotherapy have transformed the treatment landscape for cancer and are increasingly applied to a wider range of conditions, improving outcomes for many patients, though responses can vary depending on disease type, genetic background, and environmental factors.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Cell-based immunotherapies are effective for some cancers.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Immune effector cells such as lymphocytes, macrophages, dendritic cells, natural killer cells, and cytotoxic T lymphocytes work together to defend the body against cancer by targeting abnormal antigens expressed on the surface of tumor cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Vaccine-induced immunity to COVID-19 relies mostly on an immunomodulatory T-cell response.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Therapies such as granulocyte colony-stimulating factor (G-CSF), interferons, imiquimod and cellular membrane fractions from bacteria are licensed for medical use.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Others including IL-2, IL-7, IL-12, various chemokines, synthetic cytosine phosphate-guanosine (CpG) oligodeoxynucleotides and glucans are involved in clinical and preclinical studies.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Immunomodulators are the active agents of immunotherapy.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] They are a diverse array of recombinant, synthetic, and natural preparations.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Cancer treatment used to be focused on killing or removing cancer cells and tumours, with chemotherapy or surgery or radiation.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] In 2018 the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine was awarded to James P.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Allison and Tasuku Honjo "for their discovery of cancer therapy by inhibition of negative immune regulation." Cancer immunotherapy attempts to stimulate the immune system to destroy tumours.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] A variety of strategies are in use or are undergoing research and testing.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Randomized controlled studies in different cancers resulting in significant increase in survival and disease free period have been reported and its efficacy is enhanced by 20–30% when cell-based immunotherapy is combined with conventional treatment methods.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] One of the oldest forms of cancer immunotherapy is the use of BCG vaccine, which was originally to vaccinate against tuberculosis and later was found to be useful in the treatment of bladder cancer.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] BCG immunotherapy induces both local and systemic immune responses.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The mechanisms by which BCG immunotherapy mediates tumor immunity have been widely studied, but they are still not completely understood.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The use of monoclonal antibodies in cancer therapy was first introduced in 1997 with rituximab, an anti-CD20 antibody for treatment of B cell lymphoma.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Since then several monoclonal antibodies have been approved for treatment of various haematological malignancies as well as for solid tumours.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The extraction of G-CSF lymphocytes from the blood and expanding *in vitro* against a tumour antigen before reinjecting the cells with appropriate stimulatory cytokines.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The cells then destroy the tumour cells that express the antigen.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Topical immunotherapy utilizes an immune enhancement cream (imiquimod) which produces interferon, causing the recipient's killer T cells to destroy warts, actinic keratoses, basal cell cancer, vaginal intraepithelial neoplasia, squamous cell cancer, cutaneous lymphoma, and superficial melanoma.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Injection immunotherapy ("intralesional" or "intratumoural") uses mumps, candida, the HPV vaccine or trichophytin antigen injections to treat warts (HPV induced tumours).
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Adoptive cell transfer has been tested on lung and other cancers, with greatest success achieved in melanoma.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Dendritic cells (DC) can be stimulated to activate a cytotoxic response towards an antigen.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Dendritic cells, a type of antigen-presenting cell, are harvested from the person needing the immunotherapy.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] These cells are then either pulsed with an antigen or tumour lysate or transfected with a viral vector, causing them to display the antigen.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Upon transfusion into the person, these activated cells present the antigen to the effector lymphocytes (CD4+ helper T cells, cytotoxic CD8+ T cells and B cells).
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] This initiates a cytotoxic response against tumour cells expressing the antigen (against which the adaptive response has now been primed).
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The first FDA-approved cell-based immunotherapy, the cancer vaccine Sipuleucel-T is one example of this approach.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The Immune Response Corporation (IRC) developed this immunotherapy and licensed the technology to Dendreon, which obtained FDA clearance.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The current approaches for DC-based vaccination are mainly based on antigen loading on *in vitro*-generated DCs from monocytes or CD34+ cells, activating them with different TLR ligands, cytokine combinations, and injecting them back to the patients.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The *in vivo* targeting approaches comprise administering specific cytokines (e.g., Flt3L, GM-CSF) and targeting the DCs with antibodies to C-type lectin receptors or agonistic antibodies (e.g., anti-CD40) that are conjugated with antigen of interest.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Multiple, next-generation anti-CD40 platforms are being actively developed.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Future approach may target DC subsets based on their specifically expressed C-type lectin receptors or chemokine receptors.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Another potential approach is the generation of genetically engineered DCs from induced pluripotent stem cells and use of neoantigen-loaded DCs for inducing better clinical outcome.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Adoptive cell therapy encompasses three main approaches: (1) TIL therapy, (2) T cell receptor-engineered T cells (TCR-T cells), and (3) chimeric antigen receptor T cells (CAR-T cells), with newer adaptations including CAR-NK cells and CAR-macrophages under early investigation.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The first proof-of-concept for ACT was demonstrated by Steven Rosenberg and colleagues in 1988, when they showed that TILs expanded ex vivo and reinfused into patients, together with high-dose interleukin-2, could mediate tumor regression in patients with metastatic melanoma.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] In 2024, FDA has granted an accelerated approval for lifileucel, a TIL-based therapy for metastatic melanoma.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Adoptive cell transfer *in vitro* cultivates autologous, extracted T cells for later transfusion.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Alternatively, Genetically engineered T cells are created by harvesting T cells and then infecting the T cells with a retrovirus that contains a copy of a T cell receptor (TCR) gene that is specialised to recognise tumour antigens.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The virus integrates the receptor into the T cells' genome.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The cells are expanded non-specifically and/or stimulated.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The cells are then reinfused and produce an immune response against the tumour cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The technique has been tested on refractory stage IV metastatic melanomas and advanced skin cancer.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] In 2024, the FDA granted accelerated approval to afamitresgene autoleucel (TECELTA, Adaptimmune LLC), the first TCR-T therapy for solid tumors.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] CAR-T therapy uses peripheral blood T cells that are genetically engineered ex vivo to express synthetic receptors targeting specific tumor antigens.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] To date, the FDA has approved several CAR-T cell therapies for hematological malignancies, including B-cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia, B-cell lymphoma, and multiple myeloma.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The first FDA-approved CAR-T therapy, Kymriah, used this approach.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] To obtain the clinical and commercial supply of this CAR-T, Novartis purchased the manufacturing plant, the distribution system and hired the production team that produced Sipuleucel-T developed by Dendreon and the Immune Response Corporation.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Whether T cells are genetically engineered or not, before re-infusion, lympho-depletion of the recipient is required to eliminate regulatory T cells as well as unmodified, endogenous lymphocytes that compete with the transferred cells for homeostatic cytokines.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Lymphodepletion may be achieved by myeloablative chemotherapy, to which total body irradiation may be added for greater effect.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Transferred cells multiplied *in vivo* and persisted in peripheral blood in many people, sometimes representing levels of 75% of all CD8+ T cells at 6–12 months after infusion.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] As of 2012, clinical trials for metastatic melanoma were ongoing at multiple sites.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Clinical responses to adoptive transfer of T cells were observed in patients with metastatic melanoma resistant to multiple immunotherapies.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Although CAR-T cell therapies have shown significant success in hematological malignancies, their application in solid tumors remains limited.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Several recent reviews discussed emerging strategies for solid tumor CAR-T cell therapy, and highlighted novel targets that may help overcome current challenges in antigen specificity and tumor infiltration.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Anti-PD-1/PD-L1 and anti-CTLA-4 antibodies are the two types of checkpoint inhibitors currently available to patients.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The approval of anti-cytotoxic T-lymphocyte-associated protein 4 (CTLA-4) and anti-programmed cell death protein 1 (PD-1) antibodies for human use has already resulted in significant improvements in disease outcomes for various cancers.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Although these molecules were originally discovered as molecules playing a role in T cell activation or apoptosis, subsequent preclinical research showed their important role in the maintenance of peripheral immune tolerance.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Immune checkpoint inhibitors are approved to treat some patients with a variety of cancer types, including melanoma, breast cancer, bladder cancer, cervical cancer, colon cancer, lung cancer head and neck cancer, or Hodgkin lymphoma.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The next generation of checkpoint inhibitors targets other receptors such as lymphocyte-activation gene 3 (LAG-3), T-cell immunoglobulin and mucin-domain containing-3 (TIM3), and T cell immunoreceptor with Ig and ITIM domains (TIGIT).
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Antibodies against these receptors have been evaluated in clinical studies, but have not yet been approved for widespread use.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Autologous immune enhancement therapy use a person's own peripheral blood-derived natural killer cells, cytotoxic T lymphocytes, epithelial cells and other relevant immune cells are expanded *in vitro* and then re-infused.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The therapy has been tested against hepatitis C, chronic fatigue syndrome and HHV6 infection.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Immune suppression dampens an abnormal immune response in autoimmune diseases or reduces a normal immune response to prevent rejection of transplanted organs or cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Immunosuppressive drugs can be used to control the immune system with organ transplantation and with autoimmune disease.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Immune responses depend on lymphocyte proliferation.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Lymphocyte proliferation is the multiplication of lymphocyte cells used to fight and remember foreign invaders.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Cytostatic drugs are a type of immunosuppressive drug that aids in slowing down the growth of rapidly dividing cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Another example of an immunosuppressive drug is Glucocorticoids which are more specific inhibitors of lymphocyte activation.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Glucocorticoids work by emulating actions of natural actions of the body's adrenal glands to help suppress the immune system, which is helpful with autoimmune diseases.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] It was observed in a preclinical trial that regulation of the immune system by small immunosuppressive molecules such as vitamin D, dexamethasone, and curcumin could be helpful in preventing or treating chronic inflation.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Given that the molecules are administered under a low-dose regimen and subcutaneously.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] A study provides a promising preclinical demonstration of the effectiveness and ease of preparation of Valrubicin-loaded immunoliposomes (Val-ILs) as a novel nanoparticle technology to target immunosuppressive cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Val-ILs have the potential to be used as a precise and effective therapy based on targeted vesicle-mediated cell death of immunosuppressive cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The body naturally does not launch an immune system attack on its own tissues.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Models generally identify CD4+ T-cells at the centre of the autoimmune response.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Loss of T-cell tolerance then unleashes B-cells and other immune effector cells on to the target tissue.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The ideal tolerogenic therapy would target the specific T-cell clones co-ordinating the autoimmune attack.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Immune tolerance therapies seek to reset the immune system so that the body stops mistakenly attacking its own organs or cells in autoimmune disease or accepts foreign tissue in organ transplantation.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] A recent therapeutic approach is the infusion of regulatory immune cells into transplant recipients.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The transfer of regulatory immune cells has the potential to inhibit the activity of effector.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Creating immune tolerance reduces or eliminates the need for lifelong immunosuppression and attendant side effects.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] It has been tested on transplantations, rheumatoid arthritis, type 1 diabetes and other autoimmune disorders.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Immunotherapy can also be used to treat allergies.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] While allergy treatments (such as antihistamines or corticosteroids) treat allergic symptoms, immunotherapy can reduce sensitivity to allergens, lessening its severity.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Allergen immunotherapy can also be referred to as allergen desensitization or hypo-sensitization.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Immunotherapy may produce long-term benefits.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Immunotherapy is partly effective in some people and ineffective in others, but it offers people with allergies a chance to reduce or stop their symptoms.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Subcutaneous allergen immunotherapy was first introduced in 1911 through the hypothesis that people with hay fever were sensitive to pollen from grass.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] A process was developed to create an extract by drawing out timothy pollen in distilled water and then boiling it.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] This was injected into patients in increasing doses to help alleviate symptoms.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Allergen Immunotherapy is indicated for people who are extremely allergic or who cannot avoid specific allergens and when there is evidence of an IgE-mediated reaction that correlates with allergen symptoms.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] These IgE-mediated reactions can be identified via a blood IgE test or skin testing.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] If a specific IgE antibody is negative, there is no evidence that allergen immunotherapy will be effective for that patient.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] However, there are risks associated with allergen immunotherapy as it is the administration of an agent the patient is known to be highly allergic to.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Patients are at increased risk of fatal anaphylaxis, local reaction at the site of injection, or life-threatening systemic allergic reactions.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] A promising approach to treat food allergies is the use of oral immunotherapy (OIT).
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] OIT consists in a gradual exposure to increasing amounts of allergen can lead to the majority of subjects tolerating doses of food sufficient to prevent reaction on accidental exposure.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Dosages increase over time, as the person becomes desensitized.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] This technique has been tested on infants to prevent peanut allergies.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Whipworm ova (*Trichuris suis*) and hookworm (*Necator americanus*) have been tested for immunological diseases and allergies, and have proved beneficial on multiple fronts, yet it is not entirely understood.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Scientists have found that the immune response triggered by the burrowing of hookworm larvae to pass through the lungs and blood so the production of mast cells and specific antibodies are now present.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] They also reduce inflammation or responses ties to autoimmune diseases, but despite this, the hookworm's effects are considered to be negative typically.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Helminthic therapy has been investigated as a treatment for relapsing remitting multiple sclerosis, Crohn's disease, allergies and asthma.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Specifically, MS patients saw lower relapse rates and calmer symptoms in some cases when experimenting with helminthic therapy.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Hypothesized mechanisms include re-polarisation of the Th1 / Th2 response and modulation of dendritic cell function.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] The helminths downregulate the pro-inflammatory Th1 cytokines, interleukin-12 (IL-12), interferon-gamma (IFN-γ) and tumor necrosis factor-alpha (TNF-α), while promoting the production of regulatory Th2 cytokines such as IL-10, IL-4, IL-5 and IL-13.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Co-evolution with helminths has shaped some of the genes associated with interleukin expression and immunological disorders, such Crohn's, ulcerative colitis and celiac disease.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Helminths' relationship to humans as hosts should be classified as mutualistic or symbiotic.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] In some ways, the relationship is symbiotic because the worms themselves need the host (humans) for survival, because this body supplies them with nutrients and a home.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] From another perspective, it could be reasoned that it is mutualistic, being that the above information about benefits in autoimmune disorders continues to remain true and supported.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Also, some say that the worms can regulate gut bacteria.
[src:car-t-therapy/immunotherapy] Another possibility is one of this being a parasitic relationship, arguing that the possible risks of anemia and other disorders outweighs the benefits, yet this is significantly less supported, with the research alluding to the mutualistic and symbiotic approach being much more likely.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] T cells are born from hematopoietic stem cells, found in the bone marrow.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Developing T cells then migrate to the thymus gland to develop (or mature).
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] T cells derive their name from the thymus.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] After migration to the thymus, getting stimulated by thymosin, the precursor cells mature into several distinct types of T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] T cell differentiation also continues after they have left the thymus.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Groups of specific, differentiated T cell subtypes have a variety of important functions in controlling and shaping the immune response.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] One of these functions is immune-mediated cell death, and it is carried out by two major subtypes: CD8+ "killer" (cytotoxic, Effector tumor antigen-specific T cells) and CD4+ "helper" T cells, each respectively named for the presence of proteins CD8 or CD4 on the cell surface.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] CD8+ T cells, also known as "killer T cells," are cytotoxic, referring to their ability to directly kill virus-infected cells and cancer cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] CD8+ T cells are also able to use small signalling proteins, known as cytokines, to recruit other types of cells when mounting an immune response.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] On the other hand, CD4+ T cells function as "helper cells." Unlike CD8+ killer T cells, the CD4+ helper T (TH) cells function by further activating memory B cells and cytotoxic T cells, which leads to a larger immune response.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The specific adaptive immune response regulated by the TH cell depends on its subtype (i.e., T-helper1, T-helper2, T-helper17, and regulatory T-cell), which is distinguished by the types of cytokines they secrete.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] For this reason, these regulatory T cells have also been called "suppressor" T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] These same regulatory T cells can also be co-opted by cancer cells to prevent the recognition of, and an immune response against, tumor cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] All T cells originate from c-kit+Sca1+ haematopoietic stem cells (HSC) that reside in the bone marrow.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] In some cases, the origin might be the foetal liver during embryonic development.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The HSC then differentiate into multipotent progenitors (MPP) which retain the potential to become both myeloid and lymphoid cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The process of differentiation then proceeds to a common lymphoid progenitor (CLP), which can only differentiate into T, B, or NK cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] These CLP cells then migrate via the blood to the thymus, where they engraft:.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Henceforth they are known as thymocytes, the immature stage of a T cell.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The earliest cells which arrived in the thymus are commonly termed *double-negative*, as they express neither the CD4 nor CD8 co-receptor.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The newly arrived CLP cells are CD4−CD8−CD44+CD25−ckit+ cells, and are termed early thymic progenitor (ETP) cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] These cells will then undergo a round of division and downregulate c-kit and are termed *double-negative one* (DN1) cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] To become T cells, the thymocytes must undergo multiple DN stages as well as positive selection and negative selection.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Double negative thymocytes can be identified by the surface expression of CD2, CD5, and CD7.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Still during the double negative stages, CD34 expression stops and CD1 is expressed.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Expression of both CD4 and CD8 makes them *double positive*, and matures into either CD4+ or CD8+ cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] A critical step in T cell maturation is making a functional T cell receptor (TCR).
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Each mature T cell will ultimately contain a unique TCR that reacts to a random pattern, allowing the immune system to recognize many different types of pathogens.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] This process is essential in developing immunity to threats that the immune system has not encountered before, since due to random variation there will always be at least one TCR to match any new pathogen.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] A thymocyte can only become an active T cell when it survives the process of developing a functional TCR.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The TCR consists of two major components, the alpha and beta chains.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] These both contain random elements designed to produce a wide variety of different TCRs, but due to this huge variety they must be tested to make sure they work at all.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] First, the thymocytes attempt to create a functional beta chain, testing it against a 'mock' alpha chain.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Then they attempt to create a functional alpha chain.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Once a working TCR has been produced, the cells then must test if their TCR will identify threats correctly, and to do this it is required to recognize the body's major histocompatibility complex (MHC) in a process known as positive selection.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The thymocyte must also ensure that it does not react adversely to "self" antigens, called negative selection.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] If both positive and negative selection are successful, the TCR becomes fully operational and the thymocyte becomes a T cell.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] At the DN2 stage (CD44+CD25+), cells upregulate the recombination genes RAG1 and RAG2 and re-arrange the TCRβ locus, combining V-D-J recombination and constant region genes in an attempt to create a functional TCRβ chain.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] As the developing thymocyte progresses through to the DN3 stage (CD44−CD25+), the thymocyte expresses an invariant α-chain called pre-Tα alongside the TCRβ gene.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] If the rearranged β-chain successfully pairs with the invariant α-chain, signals are produced which cease rearrangement of the β-chain (and silence the alternate allele).
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Although these signals require the pre-TCR at the cell surface, they are independent of ligand binding to the pre-TCR.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] If the chains successfully pair a pre-TCR forms, and the cell downregulates CD25 and is termed a DN4 cell (CD25−CD44−).
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] These cells then undergo a round of proliferation, and begin to re-arrange the TCRα locus during the *double-positive* stage.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The process of positive selection takes 3 to 4 days and occurs in the thymic cortex.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Double-positive thymocytes (CD4+/CD8+) migrate deep into the thymic cortex, where they are presented with self-antigens.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] These self-antigens are expressed by thymic cortical epithelial cells on MHC molecules, which reside on the surface of cortical epithelial cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Only thymocytes that interact well with MHC-I or MHC-II will receive a vital "survival signal", while those that cannot interact strongly enough will receive no signal and die from neglect.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] This process ensures that the surviving thymocytes will have an 'MHC affinity' that means they will exhibit stronger binding affinity for specific MHC alleles in that organism.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The vast majority of developing thymocytes will not pass positive selection, and die during this process.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] A thymocyte's fate is determined during positive selection.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Double-positive cells (CD4+/CD8+) that interact well with MHC *class II* molecules will eventually become CD4+ "helper" cells, whereas thymocytes that interact well with MHC *class I* molecules mature into CD8+ "killer" cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] A thymocyte becomes a CD4+ cell by down-regulating expression of its CD8 cell surface receptors.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] If the cell does not lose its signal, it will continue downregulating CD8 and become a CD4+, both CD8+ and CD4+ cells are now *single positive* cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] This process does not filter for thymocytes that may cause autoimmunity.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The potentially autoimmune cells are removed by the following process of negative selection, which occurs in the thymic medulla.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Negative selection removes thymocytes that are capable of strongly binding with "self" MHC molecules.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Thymocytes that survive positive selection migrate towards the boundary of the cortex and medulla in the thymus.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] While in the medulla, they are again presented with a self-antigen presented on the MHC complex of medullary thymic epithelial cells (mTECs). mTECs must be Autoimmune regulator positive (AIRE+) to properly express tissue-specific antigens on their MHC *class I* peptides.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Thymocytes that interact too strongly with the self-antigen receive an apoptotic signal that leads to cell death.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] However, some of these cells are selected to become Treg cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The remaining cells exit the thymus as mature naive T cells, also known as recent thymic emigrants.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] This process is an important component of central tolerance and serves to prevent the formation of self-reactive T cells that are capable of inducing autoimmune diseases in the host.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] β-selection is the first checkpoint, where thymocytes that are able to form a functional pre-TCR (with an invariant alpha chain and a functional beta chain) are allowed to continue development in the thymus.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Next, positive selection checks that thymocytes have successfully rearranged their TCRα locus and are capable of recognizing MHC molecules with appropriate affinity.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Negative selection in the medulla then eliminates thymocytes that bind too strongly to self-antigens expressed on MHC molecules.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] These selection processes allow for tolerance of self by the immune system.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Typical naive T cells that leave the thymus (via the corticomedullary junction) are self-restricted, self-tolerant, and single positive.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] About 98% of thymocytes die during the development processes in the thymus by failing either positive selection or negative selection, whereas the other 2% survive and leave the thymus to become mature immunocompetent T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The thymus contributes fewer cells as a person ages.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] As the thymus shrinks by about 3% a year throughout middle age, a corresponding fall in the thymic production of naive T cells occurs, leaving peripheral T cell expansion and regeneration to play a greater role in protecting older people.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] T cells are grouped into a series of subsets based on their function.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] CD4 and CD8 T cells are selected in the thymus, but undergo further differentiation in the periphery to specialized cells which have different functions.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] T cell subsets were initially defined by function, but also have associated gene or protein expression patterns.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] T helper cells (TH cells) assist other lymphocytes, including the maturation of B cells into plasma cells and memory B cells, and activation of cytotoxic T cells and macrophages.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] These cells are also known as **CD4+ T cells** as they express the CD4 glycoprotein on their surfaces.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Helper T cells become activated when they are presented with peptide antigens by MHC class II molecules, which are expressed on the surface of antigen-presenting cells (APCs).
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Once activated, they divide rapidly and secrete cytokines that regulate or assist the immune response.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] These cells can differentiate into one of several subtypes, which have different roles.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Cytokines direct T cells into particular subtypes.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Cytotoxic T cells (TC cells, CTLs, T-killer cells, killer T cells) destroy virus-infected cells and tumor cells, and are also implicated in transplant rejection.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] These cells are defined by the expression of the CD8 protein on their cell surface.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Cytotoxic T cells recognize their targets by binding to short peptides (8-11 amino acids in length) associated with MHC class I molecules, present on the surface of all nucleated cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Cytotoxic T cells also produce the key cytokines IL-2 and IFNγ.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] These cytokines influence the effector functions of other cells, in particular macrophages and NK cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Antigen-naive T cells expand and differentiate into memory and effector T cells after they encounter their cognate antigen within the context of an MHC molecule on the surface of a professional antigen presenting cell (e.g. a dendritic cell).
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Appropriate co-stimulation must be present at the time of antigen encounter for this process to occur.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Historically, memory T cells were thought to belong to either the effector or central memory subtypes, each with their own distinguishing set of cell surface markers (see below).
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Subsequently, numerous new populations of memory T cells were discovered including tissue-resident memory T (Trm) cells, stem memory TSCM cells, and virtual memory T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The single unifying theme for all memory T cell subtypes is that they are long-lived and can quickly expand to large numbers of effector T cells upon re-exposure to their cognate antigen.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] By this mechanism they provide the immune system with "memory" against previously encountered pathogens.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Memory T cells may be either CD4+ or CD8+ and usually express CD45RO.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Regulatory T cells are crucial for the maintenance of immune tolerance.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Their major role is to shut down T cell–mediated immunity toward the end of an immune reaction and to suppress autoreactive T cells that escaped the process of negative selection in the thymus.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Two major classes of CD4+ Treg cells have been described—FOXP3+ Treg cells and FOXP3− Treg cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Regulatory T cells can develop either during normal development in the thymus, and are then known as thymic Treg cells, or can be induced peripherally and are called peripherally derived Treg cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] These two subsets were previously called "naturally occurring" and "adaptive" (or "induced"), respectively.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Both subsets require the expression of the transcription factor FOXP3 which can be used to identify the cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Mutations of the *FOXP3* gene can prevent regulatory T cell development, causing the fatal autoimmune disease IPEX.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Several other types of T cells have suppressive activity, but do not express FOXP3 constitutively.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] These include Tr1 and Th3 cells, which are thought to originate during an immune response and act by producing suppressive molecules.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Tr1 cells are associated with IL-10, and Th3 cells are associated with TGF-beta.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Recently, Th17 cells have been added to this list.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Natural killer T cells (NKT cells – not to be confused with natural killer cells of the innate immune system) bridge the adaptive immune system with the innate immune system.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Unlike conventional T cells that recognize protein peptide antigens presented by major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules, NKT cells recognize glycolipid antigens presented by CD1d.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Once activated, these cells can perform functions ascribed to both helper and cytotoxic T cells: cytokine production and release of cytolytic/cell killing molecules.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] They are also able to recognize and eliminate some tumor cells and cells infected with herpes viruses.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Mucosal associated invariant T (MAIT) cells display innate, effector-like qualities.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] In humans, MAIT cells are found in the blood, liver, lungs, and mucosa, defending against microbial activity and infection.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The MHC class I-like protein, MR1, is responsible for presenting bacterially-produced vitamin B metabolites to MAIT cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] After the presentation of foreign antigen by MR1, MAIT cells secrete pro-inflammatory cytokines and are capable of lysing bacterially-infected cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] MAIT cells can also be activated through MR1-independent signaling.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] In addition to possessing innate-like functions, this T cell subset supports the adaptive immune response and has a memory-like phenotype.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Furthermore, MAIT cells are thought to play a role in autoimmune diseases, such as multiple sclerosis, arthritis and inflammatory bowel disease, although definitive evidence is yet to be published.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Gamma delta T cells (γδ T cells) represent a small subset of T cells which possess a γδ TCR rather than the αβ TCR on the cell surface.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The majority of T cells express αβ TCR chains.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] This group of T cells is much less common in humans and mice (about 2% of total T cells) and are found mostly in the gut mucosa, within a population of intraepithelial lymphocytes.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] In rabbits, sheep, and chickens, the number of γδ T cells can be as high as 60% of total T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The antigenic molecules that activate γδ T cells are still mostly unknown.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] However, γδ T cells are not MHC-restricted and seem to be able to recognize whole proteins rather than requiring peptides to be presented by MHC molecules on APCs.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Some murine γδ T cells recognize MHC class IB molecules.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Human γδ T cells that use the Vγ9 and Vδ2 gene fragments constitute the major γδ T cell population in peripheral blood.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] These cells are unique in that they specifically and rapidly respond to a set of nonpeptidic phosphorylated isoprenoid precursors, collectively named phosphoantigens, which are produced by virtually all living cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The most common phosphoantigens from animal and human cells (including cancer cells) are isopentenyl pyrophosphate (IPP) and its isomer dimethylallyl pyrophosphate (DMPP).
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Many microbes produce the active compound hydroxy-DMAPP (HMB-PP) and corresponding mononucleotide conjugates, in addition to IPP and DMAPP.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Plant cells produce both types of phosphoantigens.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Drugs activating human Vγ9/Vδ2 T cells comprise synthetic phosphoantigens and aminobisphosphonates, which upregulate endogenous IPP/DMAPP.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Activation of CD4+ T cells occurs through the simultaneous engagement of the T-cell receptor and a co-stimulatory molecule (like CD28, or ICOS) on the T cell by the major histocompatibility complex (MHCII) peptide and co-stimulatory molecules on the APC.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Both are required for production of an effective immune response; in the absence of co-stimulation, T cell receptor signalling alone results in anergy.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The signalling pathways downstream from co-stimulatory molecules usually engages the PI3K pathway generating PIP3 at the plasma membrane and recruiting PH domain containing signaling molecules like PDK1 that are essential for the activation of PKC-θ, and eventual IL-2 production.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Optimal CD8+ T cell response relies on CD4+ signalling.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] CD4+ cells are useful in the initial antigenic activation of naive CD8 T cells, and sustaining memory CD8+ T cells in the aftermath of an acute infection.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Therefore, activation of CD4+ T cells can be beneficial to the action of CD8+ T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The first signal is provided by binding of the T cell receptor to its cognate peptide presented on MHCII on an APC.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] MHCII is restricted to so-called professional antigen-presenting cells, like dendritic cells, B cells, and macrophages, to name a few.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The peptides presented to CD8+ T cells by MHC class I molecules are 8–13 amino acids in length; the peptides presented to CD4+ cells by MHC class II molecules are longer, usually 12–25 amino acids in length, as the ends of the binding cleft of the MHC class II molecule are open.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The second signal comes from co-stimulation, in which surface receptors on the APC are induced by a relatively small number of stimuli, usually products of pathogens, but sometimes breakdown products of cells, such as necrotic-bodies or heat shock proteins.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The only co-stimulatory receptor expressed constitutively by naive T cells is CD28, so co-stimulation for these cells comes from the CD80 and CD86 proteins, which together constitute the B7 protein, (B7.1 and B7.2, respectively) on the APC.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Other receptors are expressed upon activation of the T cell, such as OX40 and ICOS, but these largely depend upon CD28 for their expression.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The second signal licenses the T cell to respond to an antigen.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Without it, the T cell becomes anergic, and it becomes more difficult for it to activate in future.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] This mechanism prevents inappropriate responses to self, as self-peptides will not usually be presented with suitable co-stimulation.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Once a T cell has been appropriately activated (i.e. has received signal one and signal two) it alters its cell surface expression of a variety of proteins.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Markers of T cell activation include CD69, CD71 and CD25 (also a marker for Treg cells), and HLA-DR (a marker of human T cell activation).
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] CTLA-4 expression is also up-regulated on activated T cells, which in turn outcompetes CD28 for binding to the B7 proteins.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] This is a checkpoint mechanism to prevent over activation of the T cell.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Activated T cells also change their cell surface glycosylation profile.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The T cell receptor exists as a complex of several proteins.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The actual T cell receptor is composed of two separate peptide chains, which are produced from the independent T cell receptor alpha and beta (*TCRα* and *TCRβ*) genes.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The other proteins in the complex are the CD3 proteins: CD3εγ and CD3εδ heterodimers and, most important, a CD3ζ homodimer, which has a total of six ITAM motifs.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The ITAM motifs on the CD3ζ can be phosphorylated by Lck and in turn recruit ZAP-70.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Lck and/or ZAP-70 can also phosphorylate the tyrosines on many other molecules, not least CD28, LAT and SLP-76, which allows the aggregation of signalling complexes around these proteins.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Phosphorylated LAT recruits SLP-76 to the membrane, where it can then bring in PLC-γ, VAV1, Itk and potentially PI3K.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] PLC-γ cleaves PI(4,5)P2 on the inner leaflet of the membrane to create the active intermediaries diacylglycerol (DAG), inositol-1,4,5-trisphosphate (IP3); PI3K also acts on PIP2, phosphorylating it to produce phosphatidlyinositol-3,4,5-trisphosphate (PIP3).
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Most important in T cells is PKC-θ, critical for activating the transcription factors NF-κB and AP-1.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] IP3 is released from the membrane by PLC-γ and diffuses rapidly to activate calcium channel receptors on the ER, which induces the release of calcium into the cytosol.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Low calcium in the endoplasmic reticulum causes STIM1 clustering on the ER membrane and leads to activation of cell membrane CRAC channels that allows additional calcium to flow into the cytosol from the extracellular space.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] This aggregated cytosolic calcium binds calmodulin, which can then activate calcineurin.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Calcineurin, in turn, activates NFAT, which then translocates to the nucleus.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] NFAT is a transcription factor that activates the transcription of a pleiotropic set of genes, most notable, IL-2, a cytokine that promotes long-term proliferation of activated T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] PLC-γ can also initiate the NF-κB pathway.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] DAG activates PKC-θ, which then phosphorylates CARMA1, causing it to unfold and function as a scaffold.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The cytosolic domains bind an adapter BCL10 via CARD (Caspase activation and recruitment domains) domains; that then binds TRAF6, which is ubiquitinated at K63.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] This form of ubiquitination does not lead to degradation of target proteins.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Rather, it serves to recruit NEMO, IKKα and -β, and TAB1-2/ TAK1.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] TAK 1 phosphorylates IKK-β, which then phosphorylates IκB allowing for K48 ubiquitination: leads to proteasomal degradation.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Rel A and p50 can then enter the nucleus and bind the NF-κB response element.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] This coupled with NFAT signaling allows for complete activation of the IL-2 gene.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] While in most cases activation is dependent on TCR recognition of antigen, alternative pathways for activation have been described.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] For example, cytotoxic T cells have been shown to become activated when targeted by other CD8 T cells leading to tolerization of the latter.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] In spring 2014, the T-Cell Activation in Space (TCAS) experiment was launched to the International Space Station on the SpaceX CRS-3 mission to study how "deficiencies in the human immune system are affected by a microgravity environment".
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] T cell activation is modulated by reactive oxygen species.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] A unique feature of T cells is their ability to discriminate between healthy and abnormal (e.g. infected or cancerous) cells in the body.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Healthy cells typically express a large number of self derived pMHC on their cell surface and although the T cell antigen receptor can interact with at least a subset of these self pMHC, the T cell generally ignores these healthy cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] However, when these very same cells contain even minute quantities of pathogen derived pMHC, T cells are able to become activated and initiate immune responses.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The ability of T cells to ignore healthy cells but respond when these same cells contain pathogen (or cancer) derived pMHC is known as antigen discrimination.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The molecular mechanisms that underlie this process are controversial.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Causes of T cell deficiency include lymphocytopenia of T cells and/or defects on function of individual T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Complete insufficiency of T cell function can result from hereditary conditions such as severe combined immunodeficiency (SCID), Omenn syndrome, and cartilage–hair hypoplasia.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The main pathogens of concern in T cell deficiencies are intracellular pathogens, including *Herpes simplex virus*, *Mycobacterium* and *Listeria*.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Also, fungal infections are also more common and severe in T cell deficiencies.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Cancer of T cells is termed T-cell lymphoma, and accounts for perhaps one in ten cases of non-Hodgkin lymphoma.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] T cell exhaustion is a poorly defined or ambiguous term.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] There are three approaches to its definition.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] "The first approach primarily defines as exhausted the cells that present the same cellular dysfunction (typically, the absence of an expected effector response).
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] The second approach primarily defines as exhausted the cells that are produced by a given cause (typically, but not necessarily, chronic exposure to an antigen).
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Finally, the third approach primarily defines as exhausted the cells that present the same molecular markers (typically, programmed cell death protein 1 [PD-1])." Indeed, it is now starting to emerge that exhaustion might not be the only T cell dysfunctional state.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] In fact, tolerization, anergy, cell death, ignorance, senesence and exclusion have recently emerged as additional sources and/or states of T cell dysfunction in cancer and chronic viral infection.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Dysfunctional T cells are characterized by progressive loss of function, changes in transcriptional profiles and sustained expression of inhibitory receptors.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] At first, cells lose their ability to produce IL-2 and TNFα, which is followed by the loss of high proliferative capacity and cytotoxic potential, and eventually leads to their deletion.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Exhausted T cells typically indicate higher levels of CD43, CD69 and inhibitory receptors combined with lower expression of CD62L and CD127.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Exhaustion can develop during chronic infections, sepsis and cancer.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Exhausted T cells preserve their functional exhaustion even after repeated antigen exposure.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] T cell exhaustion can be triggered by several factors like persistent antigen exposure and lack of CD4 T cell help.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Antigen exposure also has effect on the course of exhaustion because longer exposure time and higher viral load increases the severity of T cell exhaustion.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] At least 2–4 weeks exposure is needed to establish exhaustion.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Another factor able to induce exhaustion are inhibitory receptors including programmed cell death protein 1 (PD1), CTLA-4, T cell membrane protein-3 (TIM3), and lymphocyte activation gene 3 protein (LAG3).
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Soluble molecules such as cytokines IL-10 or TGF-β are also able to trigger exhaustion.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Last known factors that can play a role in T cell exhaustion are regulatory cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Treg cells can be a source of IL-10 and TGF-β and therefore they can play a role in T cell exhaustion.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Furthermore, T cell exhaustion is reverted after depletion of Treg cells and blockade of PD1.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] T cell exhaustion can also occur during sepsis as a result of cytokine storm.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Later after the initial septic encounter anti-inflammatory cytokines and pro-apoptotic proteins take over to protect the body from damage.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Sepsis also carries high antigen load and inflammation.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] In this stage of sepsis T cell exhaustion increases.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Currently there are studies aiming to utilize inhibitory receptor blockades in treatment of sepsis.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] While during infection T cell exhaustion can develop following persistent antigen exposure after graft transplant similar situation arises with alloantigen presence.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] It was shown that T cell response diminishes over time after kidney transplant.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] These data suggest T cell exhaustion plays an important role in tolerance of a graft mainly by depletion of alloreactive CD8 T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Several studies showed positive effect of chronic infection on graft acceptance and its long-term survival mediated partly by T cell exhaustion.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] It was also shown that recipient T cell exhaustion provides sufficient conditions for NK cell transfer.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] While there are data showing that induction of T cell exhaustion can be beneficial for transplantation it also carries disadvantages among which can be counted increased number of infections and the risk of tumor development.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] During cancer T cell exhaustion plays a role in tumor protection.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] According to research some cancer-associated cells as well as tumor cells themselves can actively induce T cell exhaustion at the site of tumor.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] T cell exhaustion can also play a role in cancer relapses as was shown on leukemia.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Some studies have suggested that it is possible to predict relapse of leukemia based on expression of inhibitory receptors PD-1 and TIM-3 by T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] During chronic antigen stimulation in tumors, metabolic reprogramming becomes defective; progressive glucose deprivation and altered lipid metabolism accelerate T-cell exhaustion and blunt the efficacy of checkpoint blockade therapies.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Many experiments and clinical trials have focused on immune checkpoint blockers in cancer therapy, with some of these approved as valid therapies that are now in clinical use.
[src:car-t-therapy/t-cell] Inhibitory receptors targeted by those medical procedures are vital in T cell exhaustion and blocking them can reverse these changes.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Tumor cells produce proteins and substances that normal cells do not.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Any protein that was not previously exposed to the immune system can trigger an immune response.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] These aberrant proteins are presented on the surface of tumor cells by the major histocompatibility complex (MHC) proteins, also known as human leukocyte antigens (HLA).
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Where they interact with cytotoxic T cells triggering a response that results in tumor cell destruction.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] These proteins may also be found freely floating in the blood and not solely displayed on the tumor cell surface.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Cancer-associated or cancer-specific antigens have been identified in most human cancers.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Recent studies show that tumor cells evade macrophage phagocytosis by over-expressing inhibitory ligands such as CD47, which bind to the SIRPα receptor on macrophages and transmit a “don’t eat me” signal.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] This pathway counteracts pro-phagocytosis “eat me” cues such as Fc receptor engagement that would be normally triggered by opsonizing antibodies.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] In the tumor microenvironment, cytokines like TGF-β and IL-10 further reinforce this suppression by polarizing macrophages to an immunosuppressive phenotype with reduced antigen-presenting activity, weakening their ability to cross-present the tumor-associated neoantigens to T cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] By suppressing both phagocytosis and neoantigen presentation, tumor cells reduce visibility to the immune system where they contribute to greater antigenic diversity.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Together, these mechanisms allow tumor cells to avoid both direct macrophage clearance and antibody-mediated immune destruction.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Any protein produced in a tumor cell that has an abnormal structure due to mutation can act as a tumor antigen.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Such abnormal proteins are produced due to mutation of the concerned gene.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] In addition to proteins, other substances like cell surface glycolipids and glycoproteins may also have an abnormal structure in tumor cells and could thus be targets of the immune system.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Normal cells will display the normal protein antigen on their MHC molecules, whereas cancer cells will display the mutant version.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] This classification, however, is imperfect because many antigens thought to be *tumor-specific* turned out to be expressed on some normal cells as well.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] The modern classification of tumor antigens is based on their molecular structure and source.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] These proteins are normally produced in the early stages of embryonic development and disappear by the time the immune system is fully developed.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Thus self-tolerance does not develop against these antigens.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Examples of oncofetal proteins include alphafetoprotein (AFP), carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA) in colorectal carcinoma, immature laminin receptor in renal cell carcinoma, and TAG-72 in prostate carcinoma.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Abnormal proteins are also produced by cells infected with oncoviruses, e.g.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Cells infected by these viruses contain latent viral DNA which is transcribed and the resulting protein produces an immune response.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] An example of such a protein is the enzyme tyrosinase, which is required for melanin production.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Normally tyrosinase is produced in minute quantities but its levels are very much elevated in melanoma cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Cancer-testis antigens are antigens expressed primarily in the germ cells of the testes, but also in fetal ovaries and the trophoblast.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] These are proteins that are normally expressed in cells, but become altered through mutation.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] The genes may be encoded by mutated genes, intronic sequences, or translated alternative open reading frames, pseudogenes, antisense strands, or represent the products of gene translocation events.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Examples include β-catenin in melanoma, prostate, and hepatocellular carcinoma, BRCA1/BRCA2 in breast and ovarian carcinoma, MART-2 in melanoma, TGF-βRII in colorectal carcinoma CML66 in chronic myeloid leukemia, CDK4 and fibronectin, p53, and ras in multiple cancers.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Some cancer cells aberrantly express these proteins and therefore present these antigens, allowing attack by T-cells specific to these antigens.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Example antigens of this type are CTAG1B and MAGEA1.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Tissue differentiation antigens are those that are specific to a certain type of tissue.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Tumor antigens, because of their relative abundance in tumor cells are useful in identifying specific tumor cells.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Certain tumors have certain tumor antigens in abundance.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] Certain tumor antigens are thus used as tumor markers.
[src:car-t-therapy/tumor-antigen] More importantly, tumor antigens can be used in cancer therapy as tumor antigen vaccines.
